In an 911 call, Professor confesses to shooting his girlfriend In a 911 call, Professor Shannon Lamb, in a slightly shaky voice, told the police that he had shot his girlfriend and that officers had to come to his house. It was important for Lamb to stress that his "cute dog" was still alive and probably upset, and said the dead woman's family contacts could be found on her cellphone. Inside the home, officers found the body of Amy Prentiss and a handwritten note scrawled on a white pad: "I'm so sorry, I wish I could take it back, I loved Amy and she's the only woman who ever loved me". According to the authorities, this was what the letter said and it was signed by Lamb. There was no indication that Lamb, who taught two online classes for Delta State University in Cleveland, Mississippi, had already traveled 300 miles to the school campus, where police say he met a popular history professor, Ethan Schmidt shot and killed the door to his office. Delta State University Police Commissioner Lynn Buford said university staff heard the shooting at 10:18 am. He said Lamb made the fateful 911 call sometime after that. By the end of the day there was another death: Lamm took his own life as police surrounded him. A day after the campus shooting that forced students and faculty to hide behind closed doors, authorities are still trying to get a picture of what motivated Lamb. The details released by investigators on both ends of the state, as well as what students and staff who knew him said, helped paint a picture of a talented but potentially difficult teacher. Students said they looked forward to his classes. Police in Gautier, where Prentiss died, said he had no history of violence or a criminal history. Schmidt himself had mentioned Lamb in a book he had written, mentioning the "wonderful people" with whom he shared his academic life. Both taught in the Department of Social Sciences and History, which has a 17-strong faculty, and many students took courses from both. At the same time, there were some propensities for problematic behaviors. One student, Brandon Beavers, who praised Lamb, said he also seemed a little excited and nervous, "as if there was something wrong with him." Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamm told him he was dealing with stress at the end of the 2014-15 academic year. Lamb previously asked Delta State University for a medical leave of absence, saying he had some medical condition. This year he only taught two online courses. Recent changes in the university's employment policy meant that the doctorate Lamb had worked so hard to earn would not guarantee him an automatic route to an assistant professorship. University President William LaForge said he was unaware of any conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but "of course there was something in Mr. Lamb's imagination." These are questions that Lamb can no longer answer. After escaping campus, police later found Lamb's trail as he re-entered Mississippi from Arkansas. Before he could be arrested, Lamb killed himself with a .38 caliber handgun in the back yard of a house about a mile south of his childhood home on the outskirts of Greenville, Mississippi, Washington County Coroner Methel Johnson said. His car was still in the driveway. It wasn't immediately clear why Lamm went to this house, but Johnson said she believes he knew the people who lived there. Lamb grew up in the area. Lamb began work at the university, which has 3,500 students in a city of about 12,000, in 2009, teaching geography and pedagogy. He received his doctorate in education in the spring. One of Lamb's longtime friends described him as intelligent, charismatic and funny. Carla Hairston said she was 15 and Lamm was 20 when they met through mutual friends. She and her friends were in high school and he was the cool older guy who tried to teach her to play the guitar for a few years. He was a heartthrob back then. All the girls melted when he was around," said Hairston, now 40 and a resident of the Jackson suburb of Brandon. Lamb and Prentiss apparently dated for some time. In the 911 call, Lamb said, "I killed my wife," but there was no certificate of marriage. They had a dog named Lightning who lived with them in the brick home that borders a bayou in Gautier. Police said the dog was fine. Prentiss' ex-husband, Shawn O'Steen said they divorced 15 years ago but remained friends and had a daughter who is now 19. "She was absolutely devastated," O'Steen said of his daughter, her and hers Mother were absolute best friends. O'Steen said he had never met Lamb, but heard through his daughter Abigail that Lamb was interested in music and played the blues. Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail were both at one three years ago Summer fair occurred They played one or the other gig together. O'Steen said his daughter writes and sings her own music. Prentiss was a nurse working for various companies online. Mike Shaffer, a bartender and sometimes entertainment coordinator at The Julep Room, a dimly lit bar near Gautier, said the night of September 5 was the last time he saw Lamb and Prentiss Night, after Lamb finished his guitar and harmonica playing in front of a sparse audience. There were no signs that anything was wrong. "Just a happy couple," he said. We were cleaning up and joking with each other. I mean, they both had a good sense of jokes. Schmidt, the dead professor, ran the freshman seminar program, specializing in Native American and colonial history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English professor at the school. He was married and had three small children. He attended Emporia State University in Kansas and served as president of his fraternity and student council. About 900 people, including faculty, staff, students and members of the community, attended a candlelight memorial Tuesday night at the Delta State campus in Cleveland. Schmidt's wife Liz and brother Jeff Schmidt also attended the vigil while the college choir sang "Bright Morning Star" and "Amazing Grace." Classes will resume on Wednesday. "We're trying to get our students to return," LaForge said. The crisis is over. This is a day of healing. Amy and Rogelio Solis reported from Cleveland, Mississippi. Associated Press writers Emily Wagster Pettus of Greenville, Mississippi, and Rebecca Santana of New Orleans contributed to this report. This story has been corrected to reflect that police now say that Lamb called 911 after he shot Schmidt, and that while Lamm referred to Prentiss as his wife in his 911 call, there is no indication the two ever met have married.
Toys R Us plans to hire fewer workers for the holiday season Toys R Us says it won't be hiring as many holiday-season workers as it did last year, but the toy and baby products retailer says it is currently at will give its employees and seasonal workers a chance to work more hours. The company said it plans to hire 40,000 people in stores and distribution centers across the country. At Christmas 2014, 45,000 workers were hired. Most jobs will be part-time jobs. The company said it will start job interviews this month and the headcount will increase from October to December. With the holidays themselves months away, the holiday shopping season is fast approaching and companies are preparing to hire temporary workers to staff stores with staff to sell, ship and deliver products.
Michael J. Fox Jokes About His "Date" With Princess Diana The premiere of "Back to the Future" was a big moment for Michael J. Fox professionally. She was also notable for personal reasons. "We were sitting in the theater waiting for the royals and I realize that the seat next to me is empty and I'm starting to realize that Princess Diana will be sitting next to me," he said in a trailer for an upcoming documentary Back In times". As the film begins, it occurs to me that I'm a simulated yawn and an arm's length away from being on a date with the Princess of Wales. Back in Time, a documentary about Back to the Future, features interviews with Fox, Lea Thompson and Christopher Lloyd, as well as director Robert Zemeckis and producer Steven Spielberg. "Back for the Future" premiered 30 years ago. "It really is for me," said Spielberg, "arguably the greatest time travel movie ever made." "Back in Time" will be available on VOD, DVD and in selected cinemas in October.
UN chief says there is no military solution in Syria Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon says his response to Russia's increased military support to Syria is "there is no military solution" to the nearly five-year conflict, and more weapons are being used and violence only aggravate misery for millions of people. The UN chief once again called on all parties, including the divided UN Security Council, to unite and support inclusive negotiations to find a political solution. Ban told a news conference on Wednesday that he plans to meet the foreign ministers of the council's five permanent member nations - the US, Russia, China, Britain and France - on the sidelines of the General Assembly ministerial meeting later this month to discuss the situation in Syria to discuss. He regretted that divisions in the Council and within the Syrian people and regional powers "make this situation intractable." Ban urged the five permanent members to show the same solidarity and unity in dealing with the crisis in Syria that they have shown in reaching a nuclear deal with Iran.
8 Polls That Show Donald Trump Should Be Taken Seriously Some have tried to brand it a flop. Others dismissed it as a joke. And some are waiting for a breakdown. But no matter how some Republicans try to drag Donald Trump down from the top ranks in polls, it hasn't worked (yet). Ten of the last eleven national polls have put Donald Trump in the double-digits lead, and some are beginning to seriously question what that means for the real estate mogul's chances of being nominated. Of course it is still too early in the election period. No one is claiming that Trump is likely to win the Republican nomination. Experts point out that by this time in 2011, Rick Perry's leadership had been ceded to rising Herman Cain, neither of whom won a single state in the nomination process. And there are many reasons why he would struggle in a general election. But outsider groups like Jeb Bush's Super PAC and conservative business group Club for Growth are now recognizing Trump's staying power and are beginning to pour their dollars in to topple him. Here are some recent poll numbers that suggest the real estate mogul isn't just a passing phase: Trump's popularity ratings have flipped 180 degrees. Shortly before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a poll by Monmouth University showed that only two out of ten Republicans viewed the real estate mogul positively. By mid-July it was 40 percent. At the beginning of August it was 52 percent. Now six out of 10 Republicans have a positive view of Donald Trump. About three in ten say they have a negative opinion. And those numbers hold up in early states. A Quinnipiac poll in Iowa last week found 60 percent of Republicans favor Trump. Two-thirds of GOP voters GOP would be happy with Trump as their nominee. In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either "thrilled" or "happy" if Trump was nominated. Only two in 10 say they would be "upset" if he were the candidate. Only Ben Carson creates about the same excitement as Trump (43 percent say they're "thrilled" vs. 40 percent who say the same about Trump). Next in excitement? Marco Rubio with only 21 percent. On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters say they would be "dissatisfied" or "upset" if establishment favorite Jeb Bush became the nominee. A majority of Republicans don't see Trump's temper as a problem. While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his bombastic and insulting statements, 52 percent of Republican-leaning Irish voters believe the property mogul has the right temperament for a president, according to ABC News/Washington Post on Monday. The same number applies in the nation's first primary state, the state of Iowa, where the same 52 percent of Republicans think he has the personality for a commander-in-chief, according to Quinnipiac last week. Still, 44 percent think he doesn't have the personality to perform his duties effectively, and nearly six in 10 independents say his temper doesn't suit the White House, according to ABC/Post. Republican voters are getting used to the idea. Putting on their scholarly hats, Republican voters think Trump is real. When asked who is most likely to win the GOP nomination, four in 10 say Trump is the best bet, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week. That's a change since four out of ten put their money on Jeb Bush in late July. Full disclosure: GOP voters haven't had the clearest crystal ball in the past. At this point in the last cycle, four out of ten Republicans thought Rick Perry would win the nomination versus just 28% for final nominee Mitt Romney. Still, it turns out that a large number of GOP voters see Trump's campaign as plausible. Even if Republicans rallied around another candidate, Trump still beats almost everyone. Some pundits point out that the fragmented field likely contributes to Trump's leadership, while anti-Trump support is diffuse among more than a dozen other candidates. But a Monmouth University poll in early September shows that in a hypothetical neck-and-neck race between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump wins majority support. He is 13 points ahead of Carly Fiorina, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15 points, Jeb Bush by 19 points, and finally Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie by 33 points. It's neck and neck with Ted Cruz. The only candidate to beat him? Ben Carson would overtake the entrepreneur by 19 points in a hypothetical neck-and-neck race. A slim majority of Donald Trump fans say they've made up their minds. A new CBS/NYT poll on Tuesday shows just over half of voters who support Trump say they firmly cast their votes. Of course, a lot can be done to change that, and no one can really say never to change their mind. 46 percent said they leave the door open to switch to other candidates. Still, Trump's closest rival right now is the other underdog, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who say they've made up their minds are twice as likely to support Trump. Six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration. Ever since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico "rapists" in his campaign speech two months ago, immigration has been at the center of public discourse about 2016. Some are concerned that Trump's bombastic language will keep key Hispanics out of the Republican Party and will damage reorientation efforts. But according to Monday's new ABC/Post poll, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues. So as long as immigration stays in the spotlight, apparently Donald Trump will too. Frustration with the government is climbing to new highs. Donald Trump and Ben Carson now have around half the support of Republican voters, largely because of their outsider status. Six in 10 Republicans say they would rather have a political outsider than someone with government experience in Monday's new ABC/Post poll. And they're angry with Washington, too. A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll in Iowa two weeks ago shows that three out of four Iowa Republicans are frustrated with Republicans in Congress, with 54 percent "dissatisfied" and 21 percent "angry as hell."
Jeremy Corbyn's debut at Prime Minister's Question Time Eagerly awaited since his election Mr Corbyn's debut at Prime Minister's Question Time New Labor leader Jeremy Corbyn is set to make his Prime Minister's Question Time debut and take on David Cameron for the first time. Mr Corbyn will rise to ask the first of his six pre-determined questions just after midday, with his performance likely to be scrutinized by the media and Labor MPs at close range. He called for "less drama and more facts" at this weekly event. He has also said he can skip some sessions to let colleagues do them. The encounter will be the first parliamentary test for Mr Corbyn's leadership as it comes after his appointment as a member of the shadow cabinet and his speech at Tuesday's TUC annual meeting. Meanwhile, the Labor leader's decision to remain silent while singing the national anthem at a commemoration of the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain on Tuesday has provoked criticism from a number of Tory MPs and has been the focus of several front-page Stories in the newspapers. Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has drawn attention A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he had "respected silence" and acknowledged the "heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain". But a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight program that he had advised the Labor leader to sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished. Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to serve on Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences on the economy, defense and foreign policy, while less than a sixth of the Parliamentary Party originally supported him as leader. BBC Political Correspondent Robin Brant says political differences are also "piling up" within Labour, following Mr Corbyn's comments on the European Union's position on capping profits. Mr Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labor is tabling amendments to remove the whole idea of a cap altogether. Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow Works and Pensions Minister, said the party was "very clear" that it was only opposed to Government plans to lower the ceiling from £26,000 to £23,000. Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labor leader to face David Cameron across the dispatch box in Parliament since he became Tory leader in the last decade. The Labor leader, who has promised a different approach to policy, says he has "crowd-sourced" ideas for questions for Mr Cameron and has been given more than 30,000 suggestions. The Islington North MP has said that the Prime Minister's Question Time is too confrontational and that he will refrain from both "quick wit" and barbed arguing, opting instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people to concentrate. Mr Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the Shadow Secretary of State for Economic Affairs, will represent him when he is not attending - for example when Mr Cameron is traveling abroad. He has also floated the idea of other colleagues speaking occasionally and that he has approached Speaker John Bercow to discuss the issue. When he became leader in 2005, Mr Cameron said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics often associated with Prime Minister's Question Time. But a few years later he admitted that he had failed at it. Since it was first televised in 1990, Question Time with the Prime Minister has been seen as the prime barometer of a leader's judgment and his leadership in the House of Commons and his standing among his peers in Parliament, although critics have argued that it has become caricature and needs it far-reaching reforms.
'Shot in Joburg': Homeless youth trained to be photographers Downtown Johannesburg is a tough place to be when you're homeless. But a group of former street kids have found a way to learn a skill and use it to make a living. I was shot in Joburg is a non-profit studio that teaches homeless youth how to take photos of their surroundings and make money out of them. BBC News met one of the project's first graduates.
